1
00:00:02,704 --> 00:00:06,454
(triumphant musical fanfare)

2
00:00:13,256 --> 00:00:15,839
(gentle music)

3
00:01:03,559 --> 00:01:06,226
(upbeat music)

4
00:01:15,831 --> 00:01:18,498
(saws scraping)

5
00:01:32,120 --> 00:01:33,150
- What ya looking at?

6
00:01:33,150 --> 00:01:34,650
- Nothing.

7
00:01:34,650 --> 00:01:35,483
What's that for?

8
00:01:35,483 --> 00:01:36,316
- For nothing.

9
00:01:36,316 --> 00:01:38,450
Next time ya want to look at
me, line forms to the right.

10
00:01:38,450 --> 00:01:39,790
Two bits admission.

11
00:01:39,790 --> 00:01:41,880
- Oh Monk, what do ya want us to do?

12
00:01:41,880 --> 00:01:43,240
Walk around you with blinkers on?

13
00:01:43,240 --> 00:01:45,690
- I don't want guys
looking at me, special,

14
00:01:45,690 --> 00:01:48,380
like it was the first time they see me.

15
00:01:48,380 --> 00:01:49,900
You see this?

16
00:01:49,900 --> 00:01:51,630
- Yeah but I got one too.

17
00:01:51,630 --> 00:01:54,480
- Any time you want to use
it, my office is in the gutter

18
00:01:54,480 --> 00:01:56,670
and next time you take
a special look at me

19
00:01:56,670 --> 00:01:59,280
think of this, suddenly
you don't see Monk,

20
00:01:59,280 --> 00:02:00,450
you see stars.

21
00:02:00,450 --> 00:02:02,803
Eh you push the saw for a while.

22
00:02:06,670 --> 00:02:07,620
Copper?

23
00:02:07,620 --> 00:02:09,360
- No it's cold out there.

24
00:02:09,360 --> 00:02:10,240
- Then stay in here.

25
00:02:10,240 --> 00:02:12,760
If it's too cold for you,
it's too cold for the law.

26
00:02:12,760 --> 00:02:15,130
After all he's only
wearing woman underwear

27
00:02:15,130 --> 00:02:16,890
and a 15-pound overcoat.

28
00:02:16,890 --> 00:02:18,720
- Yeah but what if one does come by?

29
00:02:18,720 --> 00:02:21,370
- Angelo take it from me,
the law won't make it.

30
00:02:21,370 --> 00:02:23,660
There's too much
interference on this block.

31
00:02:23,660 --> 00:02:25,590
First he stops the Pacino saloon,

32
00:02:25,590 --> 00:02:27,370
on a cold day the law needs a shot.

33
00:02:27,370 --> 00:02:28,290
- All right big shot, cut the flapping

34
00:02:28,290 --> 00:02:29,910
and give me a hand here.

35
00:02:29,910 --> 00:02:31,630
Mine's falling off.

36
00:02:31,630 --> 00:02:32,463
- Come on Joey.

37
00:02:32,463 --> 00:02:33,400
- [Joey] Yeah, okay Monk.

38
00:02:37,197 --> 00:02:39,864
(saws scraping)

39
00:02:44,980 --> 00:02:46,030
- Good evening, boys.

40
00:02:49,570 --> 00:02:51,460
- What do you want Father?

41
00:02:51,460 --> 00:02:53,550
- I swore to myself I'd never let anything

42
00:02:53,550 --> 00:02:55,980
in this neighborhood surprise me

43
00:02:55,980 --> 00:02:57,660
but tell me in the name of Heaven

44
00:02:57,660 --> 00:02:58,930
what are you gonna do with a staircase?

45
00:02:58,930 --> 00:03:01,760
We're freezing Father,
freezing we are all of us all.

46
00:03:01,760 --> 00:03:03,990
- Oh this is for firewood
but this is just kindling.

47
00:03:03,990 --> 00:03:06,540
- So we use this up, so we get more.

48
00:03:06,540 --> 00:03:07,420
- Well what about the tenants

49
00:03:07,420 --> 00:03:10,320
who still live in the building?

50
00:03:10,320 --> 00:03:12,680
But you are destroying
the landlord's property.

51
00:03:12,680 --> 00:03:16,350
- Look Father, this is
a condemned tenement,

52
00:03:16,350 --> 00:03:17,960
you know what that means?

53
00:03:17,960 --> 00:03:20,870
Any rent the landlord gets
from this trap is velvet.

54
00:03:20,870 --> 00:03:22,290
- [Father] But you're breaking the law.

55
00:03:22,290 --> 00:03:25,683
- Nobody's seen us, nobody but you.

56
00:03:27,600 --> 00:03:30,800
- Listen boys, I've got a
better way for you to keep warm.

57
00:03:30,800 --> 00:03:33,270
In the basement of the church
there's some gym equipment,

58
00:03:33,270 --> 00:03:35,563
boxing gloves, wrestling
mats, punching bag,

59
00:03:36,920 --> 00:03:38,103
even shower baths.

60
00:03:39,070 --> 00:03:40,860
It is also steam-heated.

61
00:03:40,860 --> 00:03:41,693
You're all welcome.

62
00:03:41,693 --> 00:03:42,780
- So great,

63
00:03:42,780 --> 00:03:44,300
what about the old man, the old lady?

64
00:03:44,300 --> 00:03:45,700
They're freezing too.

65
00:03:45,700 --> 00:03:47,100
- I'm sure they'd rather stay cold

66
00:03:47,100 --> 00:03:49,643
then get hot digging up
bail money for you boys.

67
00:03:52,620 --> 00:03:55,163
- Okay Father, you make sense.

68
00:03:56,000 --> 00:03:57,530
We'll go over to the church.

69
00:03:57,530 --> 00:03:59,010
You can't talk for all of Billy Goats

70
00:03:59,010 --> 00:04:00,379
without us taking a vote on it.

71
00:04:00,379 --> 00:04:01,528
- Who says I can't?
- I say--

72
00:04:01,528 --> 00:04:02,410
- Boys!

73
00:04:02,410 --> 00:04:05,330
Settle it your own way
but do it peacefully.

74
00:04:05,330 --> 00:04:07,080
Remember the invitation is for all.

75
00:04:08,020 --> 00:04:08,977
I am new at St Dominic's

76
00:04:08,977 --> 00:04:11,577
and this might be a chance
for us to get acquainted.

77
00:04:13,030 --> 00:04:14,230
I'll be looking for you.

78
00:04:18,150 --> 00:04:20,953
- Before we go we might as
well divvy up the wood we got.

79
00:04:23,360 --> 00:04:24,363
What goes here?

80
00:04:25,667 --> 00:04:27,548
A minute ago we had a whole stack of wood.

81
00:04:27,548 --> 00:04:30,298
(playful music)

82
00:04:40,480 --> 00:04:42,090
- Hey Monk, that's mine.

83
00:04:42,090 --> 00:04:44,670
I took 'em on my own time
from Brushetto's Market.

84
00:04:44,670 --> 00:04:46,904
- That's what you get
for holding out on us.

85
00:04:46,904 --> 00:04:49,571
(playful music)

86
00:04:51,220 --> 00:04:53,063
- Anybody care for some mustard?

87
00:04:59,460 --> 00:05:01,330
- He's late again.

88
00:05:01,330 --> 00:05:02,513
I don't like it.

89
00:05:05,120 --> 00:05:07,411
I don't like my son to become bandido.

90
00:05:07,411 --> 00:05:08,940
- Be calm Gino.

91
00:05:08,940 --> 00:05:10,360
Maybe he's look for wood.

92
00:05:10,360 --> 00:05:11,570
- Yeah.

93
00:05:11,570 --> 00:05:13,920
The way he's looking for
wood, he find trouble.

94
00:05:20,998 --> 00:05:23,030
Where you steal that bandido?

95
00:05:23,030 --> 00:05:24,320
- Paul, did you steal it?

96
00:05:24,320 --> 00:05:26,906
- No, always you think the worst of me.

97
00:05:26,906 --> 00:05:28,659
Some day I'm going to--
- Don't talk back!

98
00:05:28,659 --> 00:05:30,520
Said keep still!
- You hit me once more,

99
00:05:30,520 --> 00:05:32,280
you'll never see me here no more.

100
00:05:32,280 --> 00:05:33,523
- Please, please!

101
00:05:34,730 --> 00:05:36,370
- No Mama Mia.

102
00:05:36,370 --> 00:05:38,380
This was given to me by the
new priest at St. Dominic's.

103
00:05:38,380 --> 00:05:40,506
I helped him clean out the church.

104
00:05:40,506 --> 00:05:43,700
(speaks in foreign language)

105
00:05:43,700 --> 00:05:45,430
- Then it's alright.

106
00:05:45,430 --> 00:05:47,280
- I had some wood I'd give to Angelo.

107
00:05:49,771 --> 00:05:52,354
(gentle music)

108
00:06:19,039 --> 00:06:21,580
- This new priest, he's Irish, huh?

109
00:06:21,580 --> 00:06:23,140
- Yeah, he's a young guy.

110
00:06:23,140 --> 00:06:25,460
- Why not stay with his own people?

111
00:06:25,460 --> 00:06:26,940
Little Italy is for Italians.

112
00:06:26,940 --> 00:06:29,923
- Gino, do not speak so of a priest.

113
00:06:31,697 --> 00:06:33,123
He's give us coal.

114
00:06:35,867 --> 00:06:39,389
Maybe he's get a job for Paulo, huh?

115
00:06:39,389 --> 00:06:40,257
- Yeah.

116
00:06:40,257 --> 00:06:41,407
- And he's teaching me.

117
00:06:48,897 --> 00:06:50,689
- Lord, bless you.

118
00:06:50,689 --> 00:06:51,939
And through us.

119
00:06:53,164 --> 00:06:55,954
(Paul praying quietly)

120
00:06:55,954 --> 00:06:58,840
- This is priest, what
he teaching, you, huh?

121
00:06:58,840 --> 00:07:01,080
- Oh, things.

122
00:07:01,080 --> 00:07:02,710
- He explain the good book to you.

123
00:07:02,710 --> 00:07:05,692
He makes you say over
the 10 Commandments, huh?

124
00:07:05,692 --> 00:07:07,200
- What's the difference?

125
00:07:07,200 --> 00:07:08,790
He's teaching me.

126
00:07:08,790 --> 00:07:11,373
(gentle music)

127
00:07:14,610 --> 00:07:17,443
(traffic humming)

128
00:07:26,438 --> 00:07:28,337
- Here let me show you.

129
00:07:28,337 --> 00:07:29,523
- Oh, go ahead.

130
00:07:29,523 --> 00:07:31,860
- Only a mutton head would
get mad at a punching bag.

131
00:07:31,860 --> 00:07:33,210
It isn't as if it had a will of its own.

132
00:07:33,210 --> 00:07:34,110
- It's tricky.

133
00:07:34,110 --> 00:07:36,090
- Only because you don't how to handle it.

134
00:07:36,090 --> 00:07:37,550
First you sort of coax it.

135
00:07:37,550 --> 00:07:39,390
- I'll never be any good
at this coaxing stuff.

136
00:07:39,390 --> 00:07:40,750
- Well you'll have to learn.

137
00:07:40,750 --> 00:07:41,890
All you boys around here

138
00:07:41,890 --> 00:07:43,390
think fighting means killing somebody.

139
00:07:43,390 --> 00:07:44,240
- That's right.

140
00:07:44,240 --> 00:07:46,430
This block you turn your head
you're just asking for it.

141
00:07:46,430 --> 00:07:48,443
- But the science of boxing
will teach you that--

142
00:07:48,443 --> 00:07:49,870
- Aw, you don't have to
teach me how to fight.

143
00:07:49,870 --> 00:07:51,280
I can take care of myself.

144
00:07:51,280 --> 00:07:52,800
- In a street brawl.

145
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:54,670
- On the roof, in a dark
hallway, the subway,

146
00:07:54,670 --> 00:07:56,010
the park, anywheres.

147
00:07:56,010 --> 00:07:57,053
- Wherever there's three of you to one.

148
00:07:57,053 --> 00:07:59,320
- I don't need any extra help.

149
00:07:59,320 --> 00:08:02,110
- Good, perhaps you'd
like to prove it to me.

150
00:08:02,110 --> 00:08:02,943
Angelo.

151
00:08:02,943 --> 00:08:04,150
- Yes, Father.

152
00:08:04,150 --> 00:08:07,260
- Oh, I wouldn't lay a hand on no Father.

153
00:08:07,260 --> 00:08:08,093
- Well I'm glad to see that

154
00:08:08,093 --> 00:08:09,840
you have so much respect for the cloth

155
00:08:09,840 --> 00:08:11,290
but just the same I
think you're about ready

156
00:08:11,290 --> 00:08:13,280
for your first boxing lesson, come on.

157
00:08:13,280 --> 00:08:14,775
- Look Father, I don't want to fight ya.

158
00:08:14,775 --> 00:08:16,390
I'll hurt ya or something.

159
00:08:16,390 --> 00:08:17,851
- He'll hurt you, Father.
- He sure will!

160
00:08:17,851 --> 00:08:18,730
He hits so hard.

161
00:08:18,730 --> 00:08:19,563
- You let me worry about that.

162
00:08:19,563 --> 00:08:21,230
You just try to take care of yourself.

163
00:08:21,230 --> 00:08:23,910
We're trying to prove that a
human being can protect himself

164
00:08:23,910 --> 00:08:25,410
without killing his opponent.

165
00:08:25,410 --> 00:08:28,740
Come on, get on to the mat and
fight like a man, not an ape.

166
00:08:28,740 --> 00:08:31,140
- [Paul] Just remember
Father, you asked for it.

167
00:08:35,100 --> 00:08:35,933
- Come on, Monk.

168
00:09:01,580 --> 00:09:04,330
- [Paul] Father I gotta know,
what did you hit me with?

169
00:09:05,370 --> 00:09:07,860
- That my boy was sort of an

170
00:09:07,860 --> 00:09:10,290
extracurricular part of
my religious training,

171
00:09:10,290 --> 00:09:11,883
better known as a left jab.

172
00:09:13,060 --> 00:09:14,340
It has a definite value

173
00:09:14,340 --> 00:09:16,740
convincing certain types of unbelievers,

174
00:09:16,740 --> 00:09:18,040
convinced your friends, it convinced you.

175
00:09:18,040 --> 00:09:19,477
- [Paul] Will you teach me that?

176
00:09:19,477 --> 00:09:20,633
- Indeed I will.

177
00:09:21,710 --> 00:09:23,910
Sometimes in anger one forgets the Lord

178
00:09:23,910 --> 00:09:26,010
but never the knack of throwing a left jab

179
00:09:27,610 --> 00:09:32,093
and Paul, I called you
Monk to prove a point.

180
00:09:34,240 --> 00:09:36,000
You're gonna have to live with the face,

181
00:09:36,000 --> 00:09:38,710
I know you're sensitive about your looks

182
00:09:38,710 --> 00:09:40,610
but your face is God's dispensation

183
00:09:40,610 --> 00:09:43,520
and you can't escape it
by brutally beating up

184
00:09:43,520 --> 00:09:46,303
everything in the world that
looks at you or dislikes it.

185
00:09:47,380 --> 00:09:49,424
- Yeah, I guess so Father.

186
00:09:49,424 --> 00:09:50,720
(gentle music)

187
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:53,633
It's just that I get mad
anytime anybody makes cracks.

188
00:09:56,210 --> 00:09:59,810
When I was a kid none of the
other kids would play with me.

189
00:09:59,810 --> 00:10:00,800
The neighbors would look at me

190
00:10:00,800 --> 00:10:02,650
like I had the evil eye or something.

191
00:10:04,110 --> 00:10:07,000
Father, I'm 19 years old going on 20.

192
00:10:07,000 --> 00:10:08,190
Nobody can look at me straight,

193
00:10:08,190 --> 00:10:09,763
no girl even comes near me.

194
00:10:13,150 --> 00:10:15,850
Angelo's the only one
ever really was my friend,

195
00:10:15,850 --> 00:10:17,083
face and no face.

196
00:10:19,560 --> 00:10:21,426
Tell me Father Callaghan,

197
00:10:21,426 --> 00:10:24,320
don't it make you feel
different to have to talk to me

198
00:10:24,320 --> 00:10:25,313
and look at this?

199
00:10:26,700 --> 00:10:31,003
- No, no I can honestly
say it makes no difference.

200
00:10:33,640 --> 00:10:37,513
Paul, a man's face is
such an external thing,

201
00:10:38,900 --> 00:10:42,950
like his skin being red, or
brown, or black, or white,

202
00:10:42,950 --> 00:10:45,033
like his hair being long or short.

203
00:10:45,910 --> 00:10:48,170
These things are the covering of a man

204
00:10:48,170 --> 00:10:50,280
and after all I'm mainly concerned

205
00:10:50,280 --> 00:10:52,143
with the deepest inside part of it.

206
00:10:53,290 --> 00:10:57,100
Many people suffer because
their, their color,

207
00:10:57,100 --> 00:10:59,640
or their size, or their shape,

208
00:10:59,640 --> 00:11:01,557
or the kind of face
they have is different,

209
00:11:01,557 --> 00:11:04,007
but the most important
thing to remember is this,

210
00:11:04,870 --> 00:11:07,860
if you hate your face
because they hate it,

211
00:11:07,860 --> 00:11:09,420
if you call yourself ugly

212
00:11:09,420 --> 00:11:13,010
because some ignorant man called you ugly,

213
00:11:13,010 --> 00:11:16,200
you're just as guilty as he is, guilty.

214
00:11:16,200 --> 00:11:19,060
You simply have no right
to be so intolerant,

215
00:11:19,060 --> 00:11:19,973
even of yourself.

216
00:11:21,500 --> 00:11:23,943
Only Fools would laugh at you

217
00:11:23,943 --> 00:11:26,510
but you mustn't help
them by losing your head

218
00:11:26,510 --> 00:11:31,220
and besides I don't think your
face is so ugly as all that.

219
00:11:31,220 --> 00:11:35,360
After all I'm no beauty myself. (laughs)

220
00:11:35,360 --> 00:11:37,400
And anyway, underneath it all

221
00:11:37,400 --> 00:11:39,650
I think you're a pretty
nice guy, Paul Baroni

222
00:11:40,674 --> 00:11:43,424
and that's a lot more important
than being just pretty,

223
00:11:45,015 --> 00:11:46,210
and if you'll drop back tomorrow

224
00:11:46,210 --> 00:11:48,495
why I'll show you exactly what hit you.

225
00:11:48,495 --> 00:11:51,078
(gentle music)

226
00:12:05,145 --> 00:12:08,260
- Now only a mutton head would
get mad at a punching bag.

227
00:12:08,260 --> 00:12:09,313
You gotta coax it.

228
00:12:13,610 --> 00:12:14,800
Stay with it you'll catch on.

229
00:12:14,800 --> 00:12:17,650
Now all you guys are gonna
learn how to fight proper like,

230
00:12:17,650 --> 00:12:18,923
off with the coat, Pete, you're next.

231
00:12:18,923 --> 00:12:19,756
- Aw no, Monk.

232
00:12:19,756 --> 00:12:21,223
- Come on, come on.

233
00:12:22,785 --> 00:12:25,202
(wood thuds)

234
00:12:28,820 --> 00:12:30,560
Now there'll be none of that Pete.

235
00:12:30,560 --> 00:12:32,760
Father Callaghan was good
enough to let us use the place,

236
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:34,593
so leave the stuff alone.

237
00:12:45,220 --> 00:12:46,220
All right, let's go.

238
00:12:48,780 --> 00:12:50,100
Put up your guard.

239
00:12:53,456 --> 00:12:54,289
Now don't drop your guard

240
00:12:54,289 --> 00:12:56,810
just because I faint, try it again.

241
00:12:56,810 --> 00:12:59,360
- Yeah but suppose I drop a
milk bottle on ya from the roof,

242
00:12:59,360 --> 00:13:00,320
What good's this?

243
00:13:00,320 --> 00:13:01,153
- We'll see.

244
00:13:02,155 --> 00:13:05,300
Now you see, sometimes
there's no milk bottle handy,

245
00:13:05,300 --> 00:13:07,250
a left jab is your best friend.

246
00:13:07,250 --> 00:13:08,233
- [Pete] Yeah.

247
00:13:11,010 --> 00:13:12,710
- And this is our gym Miss Brooks.

248
00:13:14,120 --> 00:13:16,770
Perhaps in time we can use
this as a recreation hall.

249
00:13:17,710 --> 00:13:18,710
- It's large enough.

250
00:13:19,680 --> 00:13:21,510
Of course you'll have to get some games

251
00:13:21,510 --> 00:13:22,640
and some new equipment.

252
00:13:22,640 --> 00:13:25,160
- You mean some new patrons.

253
00:13:25,160 --> 00:13:26,980
Boys this is Miss Brooks,

254
00:13:26,980 --> 00:13:30,060
who's coming down evenings to
work with our social program.

255
00:13:30,060 --> 00:13:30,960
- Hi.

256
00:13:30,960 --> 00:13:32,090
- Hello.

257
00:13:32,090 --> 00:13:33,993
- Paul would you come here a minute?

258
00:13:37,060 --> 00:13:39,710
I particularly want to
introduce you to Paul Baroni.

259
00:13:39,710 --> 00:13:42,013
He's going to help me with
our physical culture program.

260
00:13:42,013 --> 00:13:43,670
- Oh.

261
00:13:43,670 --> 00:13:44,780
- Pleased to meet you.

262
00:13:44,780 --> 00:13:45,613
- Thank you.

263
00:13:49,140 --> 00:13:51,290
I guess you and I will
be working together.

264
00:13:52,600 --> 00:13:54,593
- Well I, I guess so.

265
00:14:06,302 --> 00:14:07,135
(Paul laughs)

266
00:14:07,135 --> 00:14:08,670
- Wow you couldn't do that last month.

267
00:14:08,670 --> 00:14:09,720
- That's right Fater.

268
00:14:11,182 --> 00:14:12,259
What's that for?

269
00:14:12,259 --> 00:14:14,600
- That's for calling me Fater.

270
00:14:14,600 --> 00:14:16,330
Well we talked about this before.

271
00:14:16,330 --> 00:14:18,958
You read the books I give
you without any trouble

272
00:14:18,958 --> 00:14:21,470
but you still persist in
talking East 106th Street.

273
00:14:21,470 --> 00:14:23,840
I know it's part of your
mechanism of being tough

274
00:14:23,840 --> 00:14:27,100
but with my own ears I have
heard you pronounce words

275
00:14:27,100 --> 00:14:28,370
like a human being.

276
00:14:28,370 --> 00:14:30,720
- Well, hymns and prayers is different.

277
00:14:30,720 --> 00:14:32,570
They're all printed in English

278
00:14:32,570 --> 00:14:34,440
and if you can say father in church

279
00:14:34,440 --> 00:14:37,320
you can pronounce it correctly elsewhere.

280
00:14:37,320 --> 00:14:39,663
- Okay Fater.

281
00:14:42,018 --> 00:14:44,851
(traffic humming)

282
00:14:45,840 --> 00:14:47,530
- Now we can get out of the business.

283
00:14:47,530 --> 00:14:49,260
Tell me, what's eating you?

284
00:14:49,260 --> 00:14:50,250
- What?

285
00:14:50,250 --> 00:14:51,910
- Don't try to kid me.

286
00:14:51,910 --> 00:14:53,720
You've been fiddling around
here for the last half hour,

287
00:14:53,720 --> 00:14:55,850
talking about this and that.

288
00:14:55,850 --> 00:14:58,223
Let's stop beating around
the bush and get to it.

289
00:15:00,590 --> 00:15:03,253
- Okay Father, I'll
give it to you straight.

290
00:15:05,780 --> 00:15:08,113
I've been watching the services,

291
00:15:09,100 --> 00:15:11,990
you know, listening and everything,

292
00:15:11,990 --> 00:15:14,713
like I told you it gets
me, especially the singing.

293
00:15:17,180 --> 00:15:21,000
Father, if you think I could

294
00:15:22,840 --> 00:15:25,015
I'd like to try and sing in the choir.

295
00:15:25,015 --> 00:15:26,270
(Father laughs)

296
00:15:26,270 --> 00:15:29,010
- Of course Paul, of course.

297
00:15:29,010 --> 00:15:31,210
I wasn't laughing at you

298
00:15:31,210 --> 00:15:33,590
but I am impressed by your courage.

299
00:15:33,590 --> 00:15:35,340
Yes, your courage

300
00:15:35,340 --> 00:15:38,740
and you certainly shall get a
chance to sing in the choir,

301
00:15:38,740 --> 00:15:41,735
providing of course you can sing.

302
00:15:41,735 --> 00:15:44,535
Come on, we'll have the choir
master try your voice now.

303
00:15:50,170 --> 00:15:51,033
- Hello, Mama.

304
00:15:56,402 --> 00:16:00,060
- Ah, I see father Callahan
teach you again today, huh?

305
00:16:00,060 --> 00:16:02,670
- No Mama, today I study singing.

306
00:16:02,670 --> 00:16:04,137
You cutting your faced with a high C?

307
00:16:04,137 --> 00:16:05,040
- No, no.

308
00:16:05,040 --> 00:16:07,030
The choir master says I got a voice,

309
00:16:07,030 --> 00:16:09,270
kind of rough he says, but a baritone

310
00:16:09,270 --> 00:16:10,870
and they need a baritone.

311
00:16:10,870 --> 00:16:14,150
You see Mama, most the
kids are 11, 12 years old,

312
00:16:14,150 --> 00:16:16,370
all they got is sopranos or altos.

313
00:16:16,370 --> 00:16:18,270
Me, me, I'm a man.

314
00:16:18,270 --> 00:16:19,620
I got a man's voice

315
00:16:19,620 --> 00:16:21,840
and tomorrow Mama for the first time

316
00:16:21,840 --> 00:16:25,772
I get to sing with the regular
choir in church at services.

317
00:16:25,772 --> 00:16:29,788
- Paulo, that's so good,
that's so good, Paulo.

318
00:16:29,788 --> 00:16:31,932
♪ Morning ♪

319
00:16:31,932 --> 00:16:35,926
- Yeah, but we have rehearsal tomorrow,

320
00:16:35,926 --> 00:16:37,843
so we'll see how he is.

321
00:16:40,881 --> 00:16:42,975
(suspenseful music)

322
00:16:42,975 --> 00:16:43,808
- Huh.

323
00:16:46,778 --> 00:16:47,611
What do you take Tony?

324
00:16:47,611 --> 00:16:52,560
Is it a dame or maybe it's
just Father Callahan's stooge?

325
00:16:52,560 --> 00:16:53,970
- Why don't you guys beat it.

326
00:16:53,970 --> 00:16:55,180
This is no place for a beef.

327
00:16:55,180 --> 00:16:56,483
- Huh, ain't he pretty.

328
00:17:00,800 --> 00:17:03,010
- Where'd you get the skirts Monk?

329
00:17:03,010 --> 00:17:05,843
- We don't want a beef,
we would like a dance.

330
00:17:07,002 --> 00:17:08,299
How 'bout a date, Monk?

331
00:17:08,299 --> 00:17:10,263
- Where's your organ grinder, Monk?

332
00:17:10,263 --> 00:17:12,780
You got the face and the skirts for it.

333
00:17:12,780 --> 00:17:14,490
All you need now is a tin cup.

334
00:17:14,490 --> 00:17:15,323
- Monk!

335
00:17:15,323 --> 00:17:17,100
You don't want to get
your lace panties dirty.

336
00:17:17,100 --> 00:17:18,110
- Hold it, will ya?

337
00:17:18,110 --> 00:17:19,080
- What's the matter Angie?

338
00:17:19,080 --> 00:17:20,388
You losing your nerve?

339
00:17:20,388 --> 00:17:22,600
- Listen you guys, Monk
ain't done nothing to nobody.

340
00:17:22,600 --> 00:17:24,070
- What do you mean he ain't done nothin'?

341
00:17:24,070 --> 00:17:25,620
He quit, didn't he?

342
00:17:25,620 --> 00:17:28,870
You know we got a rule,
nobody quits the Goats,

343
00:17:28,870 --> 00:17:30,470
not and gets away with it, huh fellas?

344
00:17:30,470 --> 00:17:31,303
- That's right.
- Yeah.

345
00:17:31,303 --> 00:17:34,170
- Now look at him, Callahan's sissy,

346
00:17:34,170 --> 00:17:37,890
and we let him push us around, tough guy.

347
00:17:37,890 --> 00:17:40,702
Monk Baroni, look at him.

348
00:17:40,702 --> 00:17:42,324
Come on, fellas, let's get him.

349
00:17:42,324 --> 00:17:44,625
(suspenseful music)

350
00:17:44,625 --> 00:17:47,375
(boys screaming)

351
00:17:52,161 --> 00:17:53,366
Ow!

352
00:17:53,366 --> 00:17:54,407
Uh, ow!

353
00:17:54,407 --> 00:17:56,603
(boys grunting)

354
00:17:56,603 --> 00:17:57,436
- Paul!

355
00:18:02,577 --> 00:18:03,915
- What did I do?

356
00:18:03,915 --> 00:18:05,681
- Monk.

357
00:18:05,681 --> 00:18:08,353
- It was an accident, I didn't mean it.

358
00:18:08,353 --> 00:18:09,571
It was an accident.

359
00:18:09,571 --> 00:18:11,659
- Help, murder, help police!

360
00:18:11,659 --> 00:18:14,260
- Monk, get going, Monk.

361
00:18:14,260 --> 00:18:16,241
You gotta get outta here.

362
00:18:16,241 --> 00:18:17,291
- It was an accident.

363
00:18:18,182 --> 00:18:20,283
- Look, Monk, you ain't kid.

364
00:18:21,210 --> 00:18:23,500
Nobody's gonna believe
it was any accident.

365
00:18:23,500 --> 00:18:25,440
The cops still remember ya.

366
00:18:25,440 --> 00:18:26,740
Father Callahan ain't gonna be here

367
00:18:26,740 --> 00:18:28,810
to put in a good word for ya.

368
00:18:28,810 --> 00:18:31,430
Monk you gotta get out of
here, to the coal yard!

369
00:18:31,430 --> 00:18:33,230
Hide there, I'll come later tonight.

370
00:18:33,230 --> 00:18:34,737
Now get going.

371
00:18:34,737 --> 00:18:36,017
(suspenseful music)

372
00:18:36,017 --> 00:18:38,850
(whistle blowing)

373
00:18:40,698 --> 00:18:43,281
(somber music)

374
00:18:45,203 --> 00:18:48,036
(train whistling)

375
00:18:54,928 --> 00:18:57,928
(suspenseful music)

376
00:19:03,382 --> 00:19:04,632
- Angie, Angie.

377
00:19:06,660 --> 00:19:07,707
- Monk, I'm glad I found ya.

378
00:19:07,707 --> 00:19:09,690
Here's some chocolate and your coat.

379
00:19:09,690 --> 00:19:10,530
It's all I could get.

380
00:19:10,530 --> 00:19:11,530
- How is he?

381
00:19:11,530 --> 00:19:12,480
- Go ahead and eat.

382
00:19:15,130 --> 00:19:16,550
They took him to the hospital.

383
00:19:16,550 --> 00:19:18,150
He's hurt but he's okay.

384
00:19:18,150 --> 00:19:18,983
- You sure?

385
00:19:18,983 --> 00:19:19,816
- Sure.

386
00:19:21,950 --> 00:19:24,930
Monk you got to stay away off the block.

387
00:19:24,930 --> 00:19:25,883
You can't go home.

388
00:19:28,590 --> 00:19:30,180
- The only guy ever did me a good turn

389
00:19:30,180 --> 00:19:31,530
and I sent to the hospital.

390
00:19:34,970 --> 00:19:37,690
This kisser of mine, this Ape's face.

391
00:19:37,690 --> 00:19:41,080
Monk, Monk Baroni, it's a curse.

392
00:19:41,080 --> 00:19:42,110
It's a curse from God.

393
00:19:42,110 --> 00:19:43,968
It's bad luck for everybody I know.

394
00:19:43,968 --> 00:19:45,240
- Shh, Monk, hold it down.

395
00:19:45,240 --> 00:19:47,190
You gotta get a hold of yourself.

396
00:19:47,190 --> 00:19:48,500
We gotta figure what you're gonna do.

397
00:19:48,500 --> 00:19:51,163
- With this face and these
fists, what can I do?

398
00:19:52,592 --> 00:19:53,696
(audience chattering)

399
00:19:53,696 --> 00:19:54,837
(whistle blowing)

400
00:19:54,837 --> 00:19:58,004
(audience chattering)

